		document.getElementById("answer").innerHTML=`These "banana notes", as they were called, had no serial numbers, and were worth less and less every month. The value of my new job lay rather in the payment in kind that went with it - some 10 katis (about 15 pounds) of rice, sugar, oil and, most tradeable of alJ, cigarettes. These rations were better than Japanese money, for as the months went by they would get scarcer and cost more and more in banana notes. I worked in the kumiai for about eight months, until late in 1943 when I read an advertisement in the Syonan Shimbun inserted by the Japanese information or propaganda department calJed the Hodobu, which was located in Cathay Building. It wanted English-language editors. I turned up to be interviewed by an American-born Japanese, George Takemura. Memoirs of LKY,1998`;
